  "prompt": "How can I survive with the truth that there are so many people better than me?",
  "response": "Here are some healthy perspectives to help you:\n\n1. Focus on personal growth\n- Compare yourself to who you were yesterday, not others\n- Continuous self-improvement matters more than comparisons\n\n2. Understand everyone's journey is different\n- People have unique strengths and paths\n- Your worth isn't determined by comparing yourself to others\n\n3. Recognize that \"better\" is subjective\n- Excellence varies across different skills and domains\n- Someone might be better in one area, but not in another\n\n4. Practice gratitude\n- Appreciate your own strengths and achievements\n- Celebrate your unique qualities\n\n5. Develop a growth mindset\n- See challenges as opportunities to learn\n- Believe in your ability to improve and develop skills\n\n6. Build self-compassion\n- Be kind to yourself\n- Understand that imperfection is human\n\n7. Learn from those who excel\n- View \"better\" people as inspiration, not competition\n- Use their success as motivation to improve\n\n8. Remember that everyone has struggles\n- People's public personas often hide their own insecurities\n- No one is perfect, despite appearances\n\n9. Focus on collaboration, not competition\n- Learn from others\n- Support and be supported by people around you\n\nYour worth isn't determined by comparing yourself to others, but by your character, effort, and personal growth.",
